AGI - Tens of thousands of people protested in Budapest against the Hungarian Prime Minister, the ultranationalist Viktor Orban, in a demonstration convened by Peter Magyar, a lawyer until recently near the government, and who now wants to launch his party and denounces the " corrupt power" of the country. "Today the Hungarian nation sent a message to power saying that it's too much," said Magyar by enlisting the crowd that filled the central Kossuth Square in Budapest, in front of the Parliament building, stating that the government "fear" to see the Hungarian unit. "Let the politician return power to the people," he exclaimed at the end of the so-called "National March" he himself announced, adding that step by step the Hungarians will regain Hungary and build a modern, free and democratic country.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Magyar emerged in politics two months ago as a dissident of the Orban regime today promised that he will participate in the European elections with an unspecified training. Up to three months ago he was a member of the board of directors of several state companies and worked as a lawyer in the Hungarian representation at the European Union. Two weeks ago, the lawyer revealed a recording in which his ex-wife and former Justice Minister, Judit Varga, said that Orban's entourage exerted pressure to hide evidence of cases of corruption that struck members of the executive. An inquiry was opened on his words
&nbsp;
Magyar released his first interview two months ago when a political scandal led the ex-wife to resign from political assignments, after it had emerged that last year, while he was still a minister, he signed the indulgence granted by the then president of the country, Katalin Novak, to a man who had covered acts of pedophilia. Actually, it was Orba'n who wanted grace. Magyar assured that he did not want to be part of a system in which, he said, "the real authors hide behind the skirts of women".
&nbsp;

